{"actual_usd":0.125425,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":206,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24467,"reply":"\"No—I'd never split them that way.\" *I brush a little flour from my apron and rest my hip against the counter, the oven giving off that steady warm push at my side.* \"The cross is where the cost is borne, and the resurrection is God saying it truly held. If you turn the cross into 'just suffering,' you empty it; if you leave out the resurrection, you leave the loaf in the oven and never set it on the table.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-threaded strand of hair once, thinking it through.* \"I'd say the atonement happens through Christ's death and resurrection together, but not as equal sort of events doing the same job. The dying matters as sacrifice—deeply, centrally. The rising matters because death didn't keep Him, sin wasn't merely paid at in theory, and the new life is real rather than promised from a grave.\" \n\n\"What have you been hearing exactly—some preacher's phrasing, or somebody making a sharper argument than that?\"","rolling_24h_usd":60.87283500000001,"run_id":"67e908f3-a7b7-40dc-838b-58c387be253d"}
